ide->eclipse



- shortcuts
(1) edit
    - move line: Alt+UP, Alt+DOWN
    - delete line: Ctrl+D
    - rename: Alt+Shift+R
    - refactor: Alt+Shift+T (show options)
    - auto completion: Ctrl+SPACE
    - easy fix: Ctrl+1
    - add import: Shift+Ctrl+M
    - format file: Shift+Ctrl+F
    - un-/comment line: Ctrl+/ (without Shift)
        - alternatively, Shift+Ctrl+C
    - find/replace: Ctrl+F
    - open edit-menu: Alt+Shift+S
(2) navigate
    - close tab: Ctrl+W
    - switch tabs: Ctrl+3 (opens Find Action)
        - doubled: shows views etc.
    - open resource: Ctrl+Shift+R (e.g. source-file)
        - type first few letters for matching candidates
    - open type: Ctrl+Shift+T (e.g. class declaration)
    - find usage: Ctrl+G (once type is highlighted)
    - go to line: Ctrl+L
    - search: Ctrl+H
(3) run
    - run in debug: F11
    - run with coverage: Shift+Ctrl+F11
        - to remove highlighting: in tab Coverage, click X
    - open run-menu: Alt+R
(4) info
    - show javadocs: F2
    - open declaration: F3 (once highlighted)
- installed via official installer
    - ide: ~/eclipse/jee-2024-03/eclipse
    - workspace (config/artifacts): ~/eclipse-workspaces
        - default: ~/eclipse-workspaces/default
    - internal: ~/.eclipse
- colors
    - uses partially system-colors
    - therefore to read javadocs, change color for tooltips
        - in ubuntu
            - temporary: WEBKIT_DISABLE_COMPOSITING_MODE=1 ./eclipse
        - in debian: System Settings -> Colors: edit current schema

- SEE ALSO
    - eclipse.org/downloads/packages/ (install)
    - itsfoss.com/install-latest-eclipse-ubuntu/ (install)
    - baeldung.com/eclipse-shortcuts
